00:32:41,743 --> 00:32:46,807
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, she passed away in February, and so we're emptying the house out.

398
00:32:48,418 --> 00:32:50,039
[SPEAKER_00]: This is Kristen's mother too?

399
00:32:50,579 --> 00:32:51,739
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, it's her.

400
00:32:52,540 --> 00:32:53,200
[SPEAKER_00]: And you know what?

401
00:32:53,320 --> 00:33:02,184
[SPEAKER_00]: I thought it was odd because I was at a baby shower probably at the beginning of the month and Kristen normally would have been there and she wasn't there.

402
00:33:02,784 --> 00:33:06,005
[SPEAKER_00]: And I was too many people so I never got to ask Bonnie.

403
00:33:06,545 --> 00:33:07,806
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, I'm sorry to hear that.

404
00:33:08,946 --> 00:33:09,467
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, thank you.

405
00:33:09,487 --> 00:33:12,168
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, we just had the services actually Friday.

406
00:33:12,188 --> 00:33:14,729
[SPEAKER_05]: She passed away in February.

407
00:33:24,908 --> 00:33:27,689
[SPEAKER_05]: So yeah, in fact, is there any of that do I have to sign?

408
00:33:27,729 --> 00:33:32,450
[SPEAKER_05]: Cause I probably won't be back in Medford for a couple of weeks.

409
00:33:33,251 --> 00:33:33,991
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, okay, good.

410
00:33:34,011 --> 00:33:34,291
[SPEAKER_00]: Almost there.

411
00:33:58,115 --> 00:34:10,158
[SPEAKER_02]: So at 7,609, I can make sure that's correct, but that's a rounded estimated value.

412
00:34:10,438 --> 00:34:11,598
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, all right.

413
00:34:11,618 --> 00:34:13,858
[SPEAKER_02]: So there was nothing big in there.

414
00:34:13,918 --> 00:34:14,058
[SPEAKER_02]: No.

415
00:34:14,138 --> 00:34:16,259
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of them go out of business.

416
00:34:26,367 --> 00:34:35,190
[SPEAKER_02]: And it might even honestly be that they were out of business, because they're not afraid about telling the city when they actually go out of business, because the wind gain is no more.

417
00:34:35,210 --> 00:34:37,970
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's basically it.

418
00:34:38,530 --> 00:34:48,593
[SPEAKER_00]: And another reason why having the 10K under exemption that the city did help, because these little things are just hanging out there forever.

419
00:34:51,194 --> 00:34:53,434
[SPEAKER_00]: She's going to work on a motor vehicle outside next.

420
00:34:53,895 --> 00:34:55,095
[SPEAKER_00]: Just saying, be ready.

421
00:34:55,957 --> 00:34:58,098
[SPEAKER_00]: for the uncollectible and re-applied.

422
00:34:58,138 --> 00:35:03,539
[SPEAKER_00]: That stays out on the books forever as far as the deputy collector, but for her, it's a good thing.

423
00:35:04,639 --> 00:35:05,059
[SPEAKER_00]: We're done.

424
00:35:05,900 --> 00:35:06,360
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

425
00:35:06,500 --> 00:35:11,521
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll call a motion to adjourn.

426
00:35:11,921 --> 00:35:13,622
[SPEAKER_02]: All in favor, say aye.

427
00:35:13,642 --> 00:35:14,662
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

428
00:35:15,022 --> 00:35:16,223
[SPEAKER_02]: Any opposed?

429
00:35:16,243 --> 00:35:18,003
[SPEAKER_02]: Seeing none, adjournment at 4.39 PM.

430
00:35:18,063 --> 00:35:19,023
[SPEAKER_02]: All right.

431
00:35:22,044 --> 00:35:25,205
[SPEAKER_05]: Take care and good luck, Ted, and thanks again, Allen.

432
00:35:25,905 --> 00:35:33,109
[SPEAKER_02]: Really quick, I meant to say this, just the next meeting, is there, is this generally work for everyone Wednesday around four?

433
00:35:35,210 --> 00:35:35,630
[SPEAKER_05]: What date?

434
00:35:39,472 --> 00:35:40,152
[SPEAKER_05]: This time.

435
00:35:41,213 --> 00:35:43,914
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, generally Wednesdays at four seem to have worked out well for us.

436
